9 PROPOSED OVERSIGHT COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
10 An Act relating to teachers; amending 70 O.S. 2021,
Section 6-133, as amended by Section 1, Chapter 349,
11 O.S.L. 2023 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 6-133),
which relates to new and innovative pathways toward
12 teacher certification; expanding definition of
provider; clarifying definition of program; replacing
13 State Board of Education with Commission for
Educational Quality and Accountability; striking
14 pilot program language; requiring the Commission to
initiate a request for information from potential
15 providers; providing a timeline for the approval or
denial of applications; requiring the Commission to
16 provide notice for a denial and an opportunity to
remedy deficiencies; directing the Commission to
17 develop, promote, and coordinate a public awareness
program; requiring the Commission to promulgate
18 rules; amending 70 O.S. 2021, Section 6-122.3, as
last amended by Section 162, Chapter 452, O.S.L. 2024
19 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 6-122.3), which relates
to alternative placement teaching certificates;
20 adding alternative teacher preparation programs to
eligibility requirements; providing an effective
21 date; and declaring an emergency.
22
23
24 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
Req. No. 16642 Page 1

1 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 70 O.S. 2021, Section 6-133, as
2 amended by Section 1, Chapter 349, O.S.L. 2023 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025,
3 Section 6-133), is amended to read as follows:
4 Section 6-133. A. As used in this section:
5 1. "Provider" means an eligible school district, regional
6 education service agency, institution of higher education, or other
7 private or not-for-profit entity which is, or will be within three
8 (3) years of being approved by the Commission for Educational
9 Quality and Accountability, accredited by the Council for the
10 Accreditation of Educator Preparation or the Association for
11 Advancing Quality in Educator Preparation that seeks or has obtained
12 approval of an alternative teacher preparation program consistent
13 with this section; and
14 2. "Program" means an alternative teacher preparation program
15 with content provided by a provider that leads toward teacher
16 certification or licensure in a specific content area.
17 B. 1. The State Board of Education Commission for Educational
18 Quality and Accountability shall identify providers to implement new
19 and innovative pathways toward teacher certification on a pilot
20 program basis through alternative teacher preparation programs. The
21 Commission shall initiate a request for information from potential
22 providers and shall provide eligible providers with information
23 concerning the application process. Providers seeking to
24 participate in the pilot program shall submit applications to the
Req. No. 16642 Page 2

1 Stat e Board of Education Commission. The Commission shall approve
2 or deny an application within sixty (60) days of submission. If the
3 Commission denies an application, the Commission shall provide
4 notice with the reasons for the denial and permit the provider an
5 opportunity to remedy the deficiencies.
6 2. The Commission for Educational Quality and Accountability
7 shall develop, promote, and coordinate a public awareness program to
8 be utilized in making potential teachers aware of approved providers
9 and their programs. The State Board of Education shall post on its
10 Internet website a list of approved providers, program requirements,
11 and the cost of each program.
12 C. A provider chosen approved by the State Board of Education
13 to participate in the pilot program Commission for Educational
14 Quality and Accountability shall offer a program that:
15 1. Provides evidence and history of fiscal solvency, capacity,
16 operation, and program effectiveness;
17 2. Provides evidence of necessary infrastructure to provide
18 accurate, timely, and secure data for the purpose of admission,
19 teacher candidate monitoring, testing, and certification
20 recommendations;
21 3. Has policies and procedures in place ensuring the security
22 of teacher candidate records under applicable laws and regulations;
23 4. Has the instructional capacity within an existing novice
24 teacher support program, the ability to obtain the instructional
Req. No. 16642 Page 3

1 capa city, or has established a partnership with an accredited
2 institution of higher education institution to provide adequate
3 instruction in accordance with this subsection;
4 5. Offers an instructional phase that provides intensive
5 preparation before the teacher candidates assume classroom
6 responsibilities;
7 6. Offers a research-based and results-oriented approach
8 focused on best teaching practices to increase student achievement
9 and growth measured against state academic standards;
10 7. Provides assessment, supervision, and evaluation of teacher
11 candidates to determine their specific needs throughout the program
12 and to support efforts to successfully complete the program;
13 8. Provides intensive and ongoing professional development
14 opportunities that accelerate a teacher candidate's professional
15 growth, support student learning, and provide a workplace
16 orientation, professional staff development, and mentoring;
17 9. Offers peer review focused on standards of professional
18 practice and continuous professional growth; and
19 10. Provides a process to review a teacher candidate's final
20 competency of required certification content standards that leads to
21 a potential candidate being recommended for teacher certification in
22 accordance with subsection F of this section.
23 D. The State Board of Education Commission for Educational
24 Quality and Accountability shall ensure that providers approved to
Req. No. 16642 Page 4

1 part icipate in the pilot program allow teacher candidates to
2 demonstrate pedagogy and content standard proficiency in school-
3 based programs and through other nontraditional means.
4 Nontraditional means may include, but not be limited to, previous
5 work experience, teacher experience, educator evaluations, industry-
6 recognized certifications, and other essentially equivalent
7 demonstrations.
8 E. If the State Board of Education Commission determines that a
9 provider fails to meet or is deficient in any of the requirements of
10 this section including failing to become accredited by the Council
11 for the Accreditation of Educator Preparation or the Association for
12 Advancing Quality in Educator Preparation within three (3) years of
13 the date of approval by the Commission, it the Commission may
14 suspend or revoke the approval of the provider after providing
15 notification of the deficiencies and an opportunity to remedy the
16 deficiencies within a specified period of time as determined by the
17 Commission.
18 F. A teacher candidate that completes a program offered by an
19 approved provider shall be eligible for certification, provided he
20 or she meets the certification requirements set forth in Section 6-
21 187 of this title in the area of specialization for which
22 certification is sought and is recommended for certification by the
23 approved provider.
24
Req. No. 16642 Page 5

1 G. The State Board of Education shall issue a certificate to
2 teach to any person who meets the requirements set forth in this
3 section and who has on file with the Board a current Oklahoma
4 criminal history record check from the Oklahoma State Bureau of
5 Investigation as well as a national criminal history record check as
6 defined in Section 150.9 of Title 74 of the Oklahoma Statutes. The
7 person applying for the certificate shall be responsible for the
8 cost of the criminal history record checks.
9 H. A provider shall submit a report to the State Department of
10 Education Office of Educational Quality and Accountability after one
11 (1) year of operation showing the percentage of teacher candidates
12 who have completed the program and who have successfully completed
13 or who have failed the competency examinations for certification and
14 the provider's efforts to help candidates successfully pass the
15 examinations. A provider shall annually submit a report to the
16 State Department of Education Office of Educational Quality and
17 Accountability outlining the success of the program.
18 I. The State Board of Education may Commission for Educational
19 Quality and Accountability shall promulgate rules to implement the
20 provisions of this section.
21 J. The pilot program created in this section shall end no later
22 than July 1, 2026.
